article_title: Rise to the climate crisis, NYC
meta_description: Flooding from heavy rains killed more than a dozen people in New York City this week. It’s a grim indication that New York City is at a crossroads — and that climate change has brought us here. The city could take the harder path and show the world how to deal with climate change proactively and justly. Or it could take the easier path, change too little and too slowly, and let storms, floods and heat (rather than the city’s own residents and their leaders) dictate how the place is to be remade. Make no mistake, the city is going to be remade one way or the other.

article_title: Keeping NYC’s head above water: Lessons from the deluge
meta_description: Waking up to Thursday morning’s scenes of flooding and destruction was a shock to everyone, — including me, and I’ve spent more than 15 years working on climate change in New York City. At an Afghanistan border crossing, people face uncertainty and a long wait
meta_description: Pakistani Shafiq Mohammad, 40, stands at a closed pedestrian crossing gate on the Pakistan-Afghanistan border, holding a passport and a stack of identity cards and imploring Pakistani officials to let him and his family through.  The crossing at Torkham, now manned on the Afghan side by armed Taliban soldiers, has long been the busiest between the two countries, but since last month has seen a sharp dip in pedestrian crossings as tight controls have been imposed.  "I don't know (why they're not letting us in), we're also standing here asking why you do not let us... what is the procedure, how can we proceed," Mohammad says through a metal-barred gate from the Afghan side of the border.
